Finding Individual Stories of the Immigrants

Here are the individual immigrant files we have scanned in this research from the National Archives (NARA) at Chicago. Each one is downloadable as pdf. Most of the documents are fully scanned. If you want to find out more, please contact NARA to retrieve a copy. Contact email: chicago.archives@nara.gov

Viewing Instructions and Tips:

Instructions:

This section digitizes around 800 earliest Returning (to the US) Application files of the Chinese immigrants in Chicago from 1898 to 1909. It includes the English names, Chinese names (signed by the immigrants during the inspection), professions and residence of the immigrants and their testifiers that we know where they lived and their social network/circle was. It further includes a "Notes" section of highlighted individual information as well as hyperlinks which can direct one immigrant's file to related ones (by the same address, company, reappearance). For searching specific immigrant information, please use the browser searching function "cltr + F" to put in key words. Individual scanned immigrant files can be downloadable after clicking the avatar of "Main" (document type) of the numbered ones you want to view. Finding guide or master sheet see HERE. Please contact/email Alice if you have any information, comments, or suggestions for individual immigrant stories and the website format.


Tips:

Here are some helpful information in reading the translated Chinese-English names and business: 1. Immigrants' names can maintain the Last-First name structure in Chinese but sometimes adapt the English First-Last name structure. One specific case is the English first name "Louis/Louie," it was the Americanized Chinese last name "Lei雷"; while "Gee" would be "Zhu朱." 2. Co. and Kee (Ji, 記, 记), or Yee/Ying Kee (Ying Ji *记) normally denotes vendor business including groceries, tobacco, and other merchandise; Lo (Lou, 樓, 楼) means a building, would refer to restaurants, as acronym of the building of drinking and eating (Jiu Lou, 酒楼)

Notes: The Co. was established in 1888 (K. S. 14) under the name of "Yuen Lung." Law Sam and his partners purchased and re-organized the firm in 1895 under the name of "Kwong Yuen Lung." More members joined in 1898 then the Co. was finally named as "Kwong Yut Chong" in 1899. It was mainly managed by Law Sam; his brother Law Toi who went back to China in 1899 and came back in 1904; and Lee You who deceased in 1903. The company has a period of hard time with accounts uncollected; stock not replenished; and business went bad that Law Toi's right to re-admission was questioned at the custom when returned. Nonetheless; it went back on the track with Law Toi's help.;

Debates between inspector were raised to decide the legibility for those merchants in China to come back to the States. Nonetheless; Plummer led the argument that the merchants should be able to readmitted.;
